#Phase 4: Build

Learning Objective

By the end of this phase, you will have:

Created an S3 bucket
Configured it correctly
Uploaded your website
Enabled Static Website Hosting
Configured permissions
Successfully accessed your website over the internet

Step 1 – Sign in to AWS
Go to the AWS Management Console.
Sign in using your AWS account.
Select the Asia Pacific (Mumbai) – ap-south-1 region (or the region you plan to use consistently).

Why Mumbai?

Lower latency if you're in India.
Keeps all your portfolio resources in one region.

Step 2 – Open Amazon S3

In the AWS Console:

Search for S3.
Click Amazon S3.
You'll see the Buckets page.
Step 3 – Create a Bucket

Click Create bucket.

You'll see several options. We'll go through each one carefully.

Section 1: General Configuration
Bucket Name

Choose a globally unique bucket name.

Example:
ganesh-cloud-portfolio-2026
Or 
ganeshb-s3-static-portfolio

Rules
Lowercase letters only
Numbers allowed
Hyphens allowed
No spaces
Must be globally unique

Why?
Bucket names are part of the public URL, so AWS requires them to be unique worldwide.

Section 2: AWS Region

Choose:

Asia Pacific (Mumbai)
ap-south-1

Why?
Resources are physically stored in the selected region, affecting latency and cost.

Section 3: Object Ownership

You'll see:

ACLs disabled (recommended)
Bucket owner enforced

Select:
✅ ACLs disabled (Bucket owner enforced)

Why?
AWS recommends using IAM policies and bucket policies instead of Access Control Lists (ACLs). This simplifies permissions and follows current best practices.

Section 4: Block Public Access Settings

You'll see four checkboxes similar to:

Block all public access
Block public ACLs
Ignore public ACLs
Block public bucket policies

For a public website, uncheck "Block all public access". AWS will automatically clear the related settings.

Then acknowledge the warning by checking : 
I acknowledge that the current settings might result in this bucket and the objects within becoming public.

Why?

The website must be publicly readable so visitors can access it. We'll grant only read access later through a bucket policy.

Important: We're making the bucket public only because this is a static website. In a production environment, we would typically use CloudFront with a private S3 bucket.

Section 5: Bucket Versioning

Choose:

Disable

Why?

Versioning lets you keep multiple versions of objects. It's useful for production environments, but we'll introduce it in a later project to keep this one simple.

Section 6: Default Encryption

Leave the default:

Server-side encryption with Amazon S3 managed keys (SSE-S3)

Why?

AWS automatically encrypts data at rest with no additional cost or configuration.

Section 7: Advanced Settings

Leave the defaults.

We'll cover features like Object Lock and lifecycle policies in later projects.

Section 8: Create Bucket

Review your settings and click:

Create bucket

Expected Result

You should now see your new bucket listed on the Buckets page.

